I now have a complete and thorough understanding of the entire system. Here is the full analysis:

---

## The Canvas Preview Gap: A Complete Diagnosis

### How Canvas Posts Store Their Visual Content

Canvas posts do NOT store a pre-rendered image thumbnail. The visual artwork lives entirely in a field called `canvas_doc` — a JSON object stored in the `journals` table. It contains:

- `meta` — aspect ratio (`1:1` or `4:5`), theme (`light`/`dark`), grid enabled flag
- `snippets` — array of text objects with position (`x`, `y` in normalized 0-1 coordinates), rotation, font style, scale
- `images` — array of image objects with `src` URL, position, size, rotation, zIndex
- `doodles` — array of freehand drawing paths as normalized point arrays

There is **no `canvas_preview_url`, `preview_url`, `thumbnail_url`, `canvas_image`, or any pre-rendered image field** anywhere in the server code, database schema, or API responses. The search returned zero results for all of those field names.

---

### What the Server Returns for `/journals/canvas/gallery`

The `JOURNAL_WITH_COUNTS_SELECT` query in `/c/Users/johnm/iskrib_v3/server/services/getService.js` (lines 36-58) fetches:

```
id, user_id, title, content, post_type, canvas_doc, created_at,
privacy, views, is_repost, repost_source_journal_id, repost_caption, prompt_id,
users(id, name, image_url, badge),
like_count: likes(count),
reaction_count: reactions(count),
comment_count: comments(count),
bookmark_count: bookmarks(count)
```

The `canvas_doc` field is fetched and returned. For the "hottest" sort mode (RPC path), the reshape mapping at lines 989-1012 also explicitly maps `canvas_doc: row.canvas_doc`.

---

### The Problem: `canvas_doc` Is Missing from `JournalItem` and Never Used in Mobile

**1. `JournalItem` type has no `canvas_doc` field.**

In `/c/Users/johnm/iskrib_mobile_app/apps/mobile/src/lib/api/mobileApi.ts` (lines 11-32), the type is:

```ts
export type JournalItem = {
  id: string;
  title: string | null;
  content: string | null;
  post_type?: string | null;
  user_id?: string | null;
  privacy?: string | null;
  created_at?: string;
  likes_count?: number;
  comments_count?: number;
  has_liked?: boolean;
  has_bookmarked?: boolean;
  user_reaction?: string | null;
  reaction_count?: Array<{count?: number}>;
  like_count?: Array<{count?: number}>;
  comment_count?: Array<{count?: number}>;
  bookmark_count?: Array<{count?: number}>;
  is_repost?: boolean;
  repost_caption?: string | null;
  repost_source?: JournalItem | null;
  users?: UserPreview | null;
};
```

`canvas_doc` is completely absent.

**2. `CanvasScreen.tsx` never touches `canvas_doc`.**

In `/c/Users/johnm/iskrib_mobile_app/apps/mobile/src/screens/Advanced/CanvasScreen.tsx` (lines 249-252), the `bannerImage` is derived this way:

```ts
const bannerImage = extractBannerImage(
  item.content,
  (item as any).images,
);
```

It reads from `item.content` (the Lexical rich text JSON) and a field called `item.images` (which doesn't exist on canvas posts — canvas images live inside `canvas_doc.images`, not a top-level `images` field). The result: `bannerImage` is always `null` for canvas posts.

**3. `extractBannerImage` cannot extract canvas artwork.**

In `/c/Users/johnm/iskrib_mobile_app/apps/mobile/src/lib/utils/journalHelpers.ts` (lines 21-53), `extractBannerImage` looks for:
- A top-level `images` prop (not present on canvas posts)
- An `image` node inside Lexical content JSON with a `src` property

Canvas posts have `content: null` typically (their content lives in `canvas_doc`, not Lexical). Even if content is present, Lexical image nodes in the content won't reflect the canvas artwork. The function will always return `null` for canvas posts.

**4. `bodyPreview` is also empty for canvas posts.**

Line 242: `const preview = extractPlainText(item.content).slice(0, 180);`

`extractPlainText` parses Lexical JSON from `item.content`. Canvas posts store their text in `canvas_doc.snippets[].text`, not in Lexical content. So `preview` will be empty or fall back to `'No preview text available.'`.

---

### How the Web App Solves This (The Correct Approach)

The web app in `/c/Users/johnm/iskrib_v3/client/src/components/HomePage/gallery/GalleryPage.jsx` does two things:

1. **Live canvas rendering** — it passes `canvas_doc` directly to a `<CanvasPreview>` React component (line 159: `<CanvasPreview canvasDoc={journal?.canvas_doc} />`). This component in `/c/Users/johnm/iskrib_v3/client/src/components/HomePage/postCards/CanvasPreview/CanvasPreview.jsx` uses a `<CanvasSurface>` Konva/canvas renderer to draw the snippets, images, and doodles live, with lazy loading via IntersectionObserver.

2. **Text extraction from canvas_doc** — it calls `getCanvasPreview(journal?.canvas_doc)` (line 141) which parses `canvas_doc.snippets` to extract plain text for the preview body.

The web app also explicitly sets `thumbnail = null` for canvas posts in PostCards (because there's no raster image to use as a header photo — the canvas itself IS the preview), confirmed by:
- `PostCards.jsx` line 721: `const thumbnail = isRepost ? null : isCanvasPost ? null : parsedContent?.firstImage?.src;`

---

### Summary of What Is Missing in the Mobile App

| Concern | Web App | Mobile App |
|---|---|---|
| `canvas_doc` field in type | Accessed directly from API | Missing from `JournalItem` type |
| Canvas visual rendering | `<CanvasPreview canvasDoc={...}>` component using Konva | Not implemented — no canvas renderer |
| Text preview from canvas | `getCanvasPreview(canvas_doc)` parses `canvas_doc.snippets` | Uses `extractPlainText(content)` which reads Lexical JSON — wrong for canvas posts |
| Banner image | Explicitly `null` for canvas (canvas IS the artwork) | `extractBannerImage` tries content/images fields, gets `null` |

The fix requires: (1) adding `canvas_doc?: any` to `JournalItem`, (2) building or porting a React Native equivalent of `CanvasPreview` that renders snippets/images/doodles, and (3) using `canvas_doc.snippets` to extract text preview for canvas posts instead of `extractPlainText(content)`.
